From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000019 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
Date: Thu, 26 Jun 2026 16:00:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] bus: ti-sysc: don't error on an active OMAP4 system timer

On OMAP4 the always-on system clockevent (GPTIMER1, 4a318000.target-module,
carrying ti,no-reset-on-init + ti,no-idle) is owned by the timer core, so
sysc_check_active_timer() correctly tells ti-sysc to keep its hands off it.
For non-omap3 SoCs it signals that with -EBUSY, which sysc_probe() returns as a
hard error -- and the driver core then logs

  ti-sysc 4a318000.target-module: probe with driver ti-sysc failed with error -16

on every boot. The timer works fine (the clockevent is set up directly by the
dmtimer system-timer code); only the message is misleading.

Translate that -EBUSY into -ENODEV in sysc_probe(), which the driver core logs at
debug level ("rejects match") instead of as an error. Behaviour is unchanged --
ti-sysc still returns early without touching the timer -- this only drops a benign
boot-time error line.

Signed-off-by: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
---
--- a/drivers/bus/ti-sysc.c	2026-06-26 14:14:04.737380313 +0200
+++ b/drivers/bus/ti-sysc.c	2026-06-26 14:14:19.900248271 +0200
@@ -3224,6 +3224,16 @@
 	error = sysc_check_active_timer(ddata);
 	if (error == -ENXIO)
 		ddata->reserved = true;
+	else if (error == -EBUSY)
+		/*
+		 * An active OMAP4+ system timer (e.g. GPTIMER1, the always-on
+		 * clockevent) is owned by the timer core, so ti-sysc must not manage
+		 * it. sysc_check_active_timer() reports that as -EBUSY; return -ENODEV
+		 * instead so the driver core logs it at debug level ("rejects match")
+		 * rather than erroring out -- the timer works regardless, this only
+		 * silences a benign boot-time error.
+		 */
+		return -ENODEV;
 	else if (error)
 		return error;
 
